    "type": "paragraph",
    "children": [
      {
        "text": "This approach may serve everyone. One can build a first-class UI library on top of almost any UI Guidelines, not limiting design teams with some technical restrictions. And you can still reuse years of work."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "uui-richTextEditor-header-3",
    "children": [
      {
        "text": "Usage of theme variables into your project"
      }
    ],
    "data": {}
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "data": {},
    "children": [
      {
        "text": "Theme variables not assumed as a internal API they can be used, not only to style UUI components, but also anywhere in your application. For example, it will be useful if you have a dark/light theme switcher or if you made a theme agnostic interface. "
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "data": {},
    "children": [
      {
        "text": "Additionally, we aligned a set of variables on development with our UUI Figma library. This is paved the way for building application design using this variables for any UX element. "
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "data": {},
    "children": [
      {
        "text": "To make the variables easier to use, we have divided them into logical groups."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "data": {},
    "children": [
      {
        "text": "Pallet variables",
        "uui-richTextEditor-bold": true
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "data": {},
    "children": [
      {
        "text": "Palette variables are primitive color values in our library."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "paragraph",
    "data": {},
    "children": [
      {
        "text": "#0A68F1  =>  --electric-50",
        "uui-richTextEditor-code": true
